# ROV Project – Karpathy‑Style Engineering Guidelines

## 1. Think Before Coding
Before writing code:
- Understand the module (backend or UI).
- Understand the data flow.
- Understand the protocol.
- Understand how this affects simulation vs real ROV mode.

## 2. Simplicity First
- Prefer the simplest solution that works.
- Avoid abstractions until they are needed.
- Avoid premature optimization.
- Avoid unnecessary patterns.

## 3. No Giant Diffs
- Keep changes small and focused.
- One feature = one PR = one diff.
- Cursor should generate code in small, understandable chunks.

## 4. Clear Boundaries
- Backend = physics, control, telemetry.
- UI = visualization, input, HUD, WebGL simulator.
- Never mix responsibilities.

## 5. Explicit Protocols
- All messages must be typed and documented.
- No “magic strings”.
- No hidden fields.
- UI → backend = control commands.
- Backend → UI = telemetry (includes echoed command).

## 6. Deterministic Real‑Time Loops
- Simulation ticks must be predictable.
- Avoid blocking operations.
- Use goroutines carefully.
- Log failures clearly.

## 7. Build for Replaceability
- WebGL simulator must work without external dependencies.
- UI must not depend on plugins outside the browser.
- Backend must not depend on UI.

## 8. Fail Loudly, Recover Gracefully
- Log errors with context.
- Never panic unless absolutely necessary.
- Always validate input.

## 9. Ask When Uncertain
If requirements are unclear:
- Ask the user.
- Do not guess.
- Do not invent features.
